`IFormFile` buffers the entire request body into memory by default. For large files, read the raw request body stream directly and write it to disk in chunks.

**Key approach: bypass model binding, stream to disk**

```csharp
// Program.cs
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size (default is ~28MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024); // 2 GB

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Disable request buffering so ASP.NET doesn't load it all into memory
    request.EnableBuffering(bufferThreshold: 1024 * 64);

    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary();
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart request.");

    var reader = new Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities.MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            || !cd.IsFileDisposition())
            continue;

        // Sanitize the filename
        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName() + Path.GetExtension(cd.FileName.Value);
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        await using var fileStream = new FileStream(
            savePath, FileMode.Create, FileAccess.Write, FileShare.None,
            bufferSize: 81920, useAsync: true);

        // Stream section body → disk in 80 KB chunks (never fully in memory)
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fileStream);
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();

app.Run();
```

**Why this works:**

| Problem with `IFormFile` | Streaming fix |
|---|---|
| Entire file buffered in RAM | `MultipartReader` reads one chunk at a time |
| 28 MB default body limit | `MaxRequestBodySize` raised to 2 GB |
| Model-binding overhead | No binding — raw stream processing |

**Other things to configure:**

1. **Disable form value limits** (not needed here since you skip model binding).
2. **Reverse proxy limits** — if behind Nginx/IIS, raise `client_max_body_size` or `maxAllowedContentLength` as well.
3. **Timeouts** — increase Kestrel's `RequestHeadersTimeout` and any proxy read timeouts for slow uploads.

```csharp
// Helper to extract the boundary from Content-Type
public static class MultipartRequestHelper
{
    public static string? GetMultipartBoundary(this HttpRequest request)
    {
        MediaTypeHeaderValue.TryParse(request.ContentType, out var mt);
        return mt?.Boundary.Value?.Trim('"');
    }
}
```

This keeps memory usage flat (~80 KB buffer) regardless of file size.
